        content: 'Modern vehicles increasingly use dual-clutch transmissions (DCTs) or continuously variable transmissions (CVTs) rather than traditional stepped automatics, and these units require explicit coverage confirmation before relying on MBI. DCTs — used in Volkswagen/Audi DSG, Hyundai/Kia DCT, Ford PowerShift, BMW M-DCT, and similar — are dry or wet multi-plate clutch systems controlled by electronics and hydraulics. They share some architecture with conventional automatics but differ in their clutch wear characteristics and failure modes. CVTs — used in Nissan (Jatco), Subaru Lineartronic, Honda CVT, Mitsubishi Invecs, and many others — use a belt-and-pulley system that is fundamentally different from stepped transmissions and has its own failure profile. CVT belt slippage, pulley wear, and bearing failures are CVT-specific events that not all "automatic transmission" coverage explicitly addresses. Not all MBI policies that cover "automatic transmissions" include DCT or CVT units in their scope — the policy wording matters significantly. Before relying on MBI for a CVT or DCT vehicle, ask the provider explicitly: are CVT belt-and-pulley failures covered? Are DCT clutch pack failures covered under my transmission component schedule? Get confirmation in writing, not just verbally. Our comparison tool identifies which providers explicitly cover DCT and CVT failures for common vehicle makes and models.',
